<section id="why-quarto" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="why-quarto">Why Quarto?</h2>
<p>As a graduate student in Biochemistry, Microbiology, and Molecular Biology at Penn State, I needed a professional website to showcase my CV and share updates about my research. I initially started with a simple Jekyll-based GitHub Pages site, but I wanted something more flexible and powerful.</p>
<p>Enter <a href="https://quarto.org/">Quarto</a> - an open-source scientific and technical publishing system that’s perfect for academics. Here’s why I made the switch:</p>
<section id="key-advantages" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="key-advantages">Key Advantages</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li><p><strong>Computational Integration</strong>: Quarto can embed R, Python, and Julia code, which is perfect for sharing research analyses and visualizations in future blog posts.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Superior PDF Export</strong>: I can easily export my CV to PDF with consistent formatting - essential for job applications and conference submissions.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Modern Tooling</strong>: Quarto is actively developed by Posit (formerly RStudio) and has excellent documentation and community support.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Unified Publishing</strong>: One system for websites, presentations, papers, and books. As I progress through my PhD, I can use Quarto for dissertation chapters, posters, and more.</p></li>
</ol>
</section>
</section>
<section id="the-conversion-process" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-conversion-process">The Conversion Process</h2>
<section id="from-jekyll-to-quarto" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="from-jekyll-to-quarto">From Jekyll to Quarto</h3>
<p>The conversion was surprisingly straightforward:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p><strong>Configuration</strong>: I replaced <code>_config.yml</code> with <code>_quarto.yml</code>, which defines the site structure, navigation, and theme.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Content</strong>: My CV (<code>index.md</code>) became <code>index.qmd</code> with just a YAML header addition. All the Markdown content stayed identical - Quarto is fully compatible with standard Markdown.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Theme</strong>: I chose the <code>cosmo</code> theme for its clean, professional appearance. It’s similar to Jekyll’s minimal theme but more customizable.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Blog Setup</strong>: I created a <code>blog.qmd</code> listing page that automatically aggregates posts from the <code>posts/</code> directory, sorted chronologically.</p></li>
</ol>
</section>
