<section id="repository-configuration" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="repository-configuration">Repository Configuration</h3>
<p>Two critical GitHub settings were required:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>Actions Permissions</strong>: Settings → Actions → General → Set “Read and write permissions”</li>
<li><strong>Pages Source</strong>: Settings → Pages → Deploy from branch: <code>gh-pages</code> / <code>root</code></li>
</ol>
</section>
</section>
<section id="what-i-learned" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="what-i-learned">What I Learned</h2>
<section id="challenges" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="challenges">Challenges</h3>
<p><strong>GitHub Actions Permissions</strong>: Initially, my workflow failed because GitHub Actions didn’t have write permissions. The fix was simple but not immediately obvious.</p>
<p><strong>Branch Deployment</strong>: I chose the <code>gh-pages</code> branch approach over the <code>docs/</code> folder method. It keeps the main branch cleaner and follows standard conventions.</p>
</section>
<section id="benefits" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="benefits">Benefits</h3>
<p><strong>Markdown Compatibility</strong>: All my existing content worked perfectly - no reformatting needed.</p>
<p><strong>Extensibility</strong>: I can now easily add computational content, interactive visualizations, and more sophisticated layouts as my needs grow.</p>
<p><strong>Professional Appearance</strong>: The site looks polished and modern, which is important for making a good impression on potential collaborators and employers.</p>
</section>
</section>
<section id="future-plans" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="future-plans">Future Plans</h2>
<p>Now that the infrastructure is in place, I plan to use this blog for:</p>
<ul>
<li>Sharing updates about my research on IS1-mediated chromosomal amplification in <em>E. coli</em></li>
<li>Documenting computational methods and analyses</li>
<li>Writing about conferences and workshops I attend</li>
<li>Sharing insights about graduate school in BMMB</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="resources" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="resources">Resources</h2>
<p>If you’re considering a similar setup, these resources were invaluable:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://quarto.org/docs/guide/">Quarto Documentation</a></li>
<li><a href="https://quarto.org/docs/websites/">Quarto for Academics Guide</a></li>
<li><a href="https://github.com/quarto-dev/quarto-actions">GitHub Actions for Quarto</a></li>
</ul>
<p>The entire source code for this website is available on <a href="https://github.com/Bri-W12/CV">GitHub</a>. Feel free to fork it and adapt it for your own academic website!</p>
<hr>
<p><strong>Technical Details:</strong> - Platform: Quarto 1.4+ - Hosting: GitHub Pages - Theme: Cosmo - Deployment: GitHub Actions (automated) - Repository: <a href="https://github.com/Bri-W12/CV">Bri-W12/CV</a></p>


